VSo, I had been a photographer
p4
aVfor 18 years
p5
aVbefore I began the Microsculpture Project.
p6
aVAnd in that time, I had shot global ad campaigns,
p7
aVI had the opportunity to photograph some of my generation's icons,
p8
aVand I was traveling the world.
p9
aVI got to a point in my career that I dreamed of getting to,
p10
aVand yet, for some reason, I still felt a little bit unfulfilled.
p11
aVDespite the extraordinary things I was shooting and experiencing,
p12
aVthey'd started to feel a little bit ordinary to me.
p13
aVI was also getting concerned
p14
aVabout how disposable photography had started to feel in the digital world,
p15
aVand I really wanted to produce images that had a sense of worth again.
p16
aVAnd I needed a subject that felt extraordinary.
p17
aa(lp18
VSometimes I wish I had the eyes of a child.
p19
aVAnd by that I mean, I wish I could look at the world
p20
aVin the same as I did when I was a small boy.
p21
aVI think there is a danger, as we get older,
p22
aVthat our curiosity becomes slightly muted or dulled by familiarity.
p23
aVAnd as a visual creator, one of the challenges for me
p24
aVis to present the familiar in a new and engaging way.
