aa(lp45
VSo I decided to photograph it for him, and this is what I produced.
p46
aVI basically asked myself two simple questions.
p47
aVThe first one:
p48
aVCould I take all my knowledge and skill of photographic lighting
p49
aVand take that onto a subject that's five millimeters long?
p50
aVBut also: Could I keep creative control over that lighting
p51
aVon a subject that size?
p52
aVSo I practiced on some other found specimens,
p53
aVand I approached the Oxford University Museum of Natural History
p54
aVto see if I could have access to their collection,
p55
aVto progress the project.
p56
aVAnd I went up there for a meeting,
p57
aVand I showed them some of the images that I'd been shooting,
p58
aVand they could see the kind of detail I was able to get.
p59
aVI don't think they'd ever really seen anything quite like it before,
p60
aVand from that point forward, they gave me open access
p61
aVto their entire collection
p62
aVand the assistance of Dr. James Hogan, their entomologist.
p63
aa(lp64
VNow, over the next two-and-a-half years,
p65
aVI shot 37 insects from their collection.
p66
aVAnd the way I work
p67
aVis that I essentially split the insect up into multiple sections,
p68
aVand I treat each one of those sections like a small still life.
p69
aVSo for example, if I was photographing the eye of the insect,
p70
aVwhich is normally quite smooth and dome-shaped,
p71
aVthen I'd use a light source that is large and soft and diffuse,
p72
aVso I don't get any harsh hot spots on that surface.
p73
aVBut once my attention turns over to a hairy leg,
p74
aVthat lighting setup will change completely.
p75
aVAnd so I make that one tiny section look as beautiful as I possibly can,
p76
aVand I work my way across the insect
p77
aVuntil I have about 20 or 25 different sections.
p78
aa(lp79
VThe issue with photography at high magnification
p80
aVis that there is inherently a very shallow depth of field.
p81
aVSo to get around that, what I do is,
p82
aVI put my camera on a rail
p83
aVthat I can automate to move 10 microns in between each shot.
p84
aVThat's about one-seventh the width of a human hair.
p85
aVAnd then that provides me with a deep stack of images.
p86
aVEach has a tiny sliver of focus all the way through.
p87
aVAnd I can squash that down
p88
aVto produce one image that is fully focused from front to back.
p89
aVSo essentially, that gives me 25 sections that are fully focused
p90
aVand beautifully lit.
p91
aVNow, each one of my images
p92
aVis made up of anywhere between 8- and 10,000 separate shots.
p93
aVThey take about three-and-a-half weeks to create,
p94
aVand the file sizes on average are about four gigabytes.
p95
aVSo I've got plenty of information to play with when I'm printing.
p96
aVAnd the prints at the exhibition are around the three-meter mark.
p97
aVIn fact, I had a show in Milan two weeks ago,
p98
aVand we had some prints there that were nine meters long.
p99
aa(lp100
VBut, you know, I realize
p101
aVthat these images still have to work in the digital world.
p102
aVThere's no point in me putting all my blood, sweat and tears
p103
aVinto these pictures
p104
aVif they're only going to be showing 500 pixels on a screen.
